Human Activity Recognition with Smartphones - Supervised Machine Learning¶

Sarah Santos - Esteban O. Lopez

This notebook aims at finding the optimal classifier for the problem of Human Activity Recognition. A problem in which the data obtained by messuring the movement and speed of a person performing different physical activities while wearing a device.

Data

The dataset used is found in kaggle: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/uciml/human-activity-recognition-with-smartphones?datasetId=226 Related research: Davide Anguita, Alessandro Ghio, Luca Oneto, Xavier Parra and Jorge L. Reyes-Ortiz. A Public Domain Dataset for Human Activity Recognition Using Smartphones. 21st European Symposium on Artificial Neural Networks, Computational Intelligence and Machine Learning, ESANN 2013. Bruges, Belgium 24-26 April 2013

The dataset is composed of several variables all product of the observation of sensors in devices carried by people subject of an experiment. The attribute information according to the source, for each record in the dataset the following is provided:

  • Triaxial acceleration from the accelerometer (total acceleration) and the estimated body acceleration.

  • Triaxial Angular velocity from the gyroscope.

  • A 561-feature vector with time and frequency domain variables.

  • Its activity label.

  • An identifier of the subject who carried out the experiment.

The data is already divided into train an test sets. The files are previously downloaded and saved in the "data" folder.

Data Processing 1: PCA¶

  • A print_score function is set to compare results between train and test results of the different models
In [28]:
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, confusion_matrix, classification_report

def print_score(clf, X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test, train=True):
    if train:
        pred = clf.predict(X_train)
        clf_report = pd.DataFrame(classification_report(y_train, pred, output_dict=True))
        print("Train Result:\n================================================")
        print(f"Accuracy Score: {accuracy_score(y_train, pred) * 100:.2f}%")
        print("_______________________________________________")
        print(f"CLASSIFICATION REPORT:\n{clf_report}")
        print("_______________________________________________")
        print(f"Confusion Matrix: \n {confusion_matrix(y_train, pred)}\n")
        
    elif train==False:
        pred = clf.predict(X_test)
        clf_report = pd.DataFrame(classification_report(y_test, pred, output_dict=True))
        print("Test Result:\n================================================")        
        print(f"Accuracy Score: {accuracy_score(y_test, pred) * 100:.2f}%")
        print("_______________________________________________")
        print(f"CLASSIFICATION REPORT:\n{clf_report}")
        print("_______________________________________________")
        print(f"Confusion Matrix: \n {confusion_matrix(y_test, pred)}\n")
  • For both data sets the "subject" variable will be droped.

In [32]:
variance = 0 # variance explained by the components
component = 0 #number of components 
for i in pca.explained_variance_ratio_:
    variance = variance + i
    component = component + 1
    if variance > 0.90: # we will use the components required to explain 90% of the variance in the set. We could use more, but the gain in variance for each additional component might not be worth it
        print(f"We can see that {variance}% of the variance is explained by the first {component} components")
        break

Data Modeling 1¶

  • On the next part of the process different classification algorithms are performed to find the most appropriate classifier for this problem.
  • The algorithms will be trained on the training set previously defined. The algorithms performed use cross validation on the training set to optimze the hyperparameters of the models.
  • The test set previously defined is therefore used as a "validation" set. For this, the selection of the algorithm will be based on the performance on the test set.
  • Since we have considered data is not too unbalanced and that there is not specific cost for missclassification, the scoring for all models will be the estimated accuracy of the model on the test set.
  • All the models selected are from the sklearn package, except for the XGBoost model, which has its own library.

1. Logistic Regression¶

  • A multinomial logistic regresion is fit.
  • Docummentation on the logistic regression class: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.linear_model.LogisticRegression.html
  • Optimization of the model is achieved by GridSearchCV. This package allows to estimate a series of models using a combination of different sets of parameters. The best model will be selected according to the performance on cross validation. Docummentation: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.model_selection.GridSearchCV.html
In [41]:
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

#creating a set of parameters to be tried by 
params = {"penalty": ["l2", None], 
          "C": np.logspace(-4, 4, 20),
          "class_weight" :["balanced", None], #different possibilites accounting for inbalancing problems
          "solver": ["sag", "saga"]} #algorithms that work for multiclass problems

#the instance of the classifier is defined
lr_clf = LogisticRegression(multi_class='multinomial')

#the indstance of the crossvalidation grid search is defined
lr_cv = GridSearchCV(lr_clf, params, scoring="accuracy", n_jobs=-1, verbose=0, cv=5) #the classifier is used, in the grid of parameters defined, score is accuracy and 5 folds are created for cross validation
lr_cv.fit(x_train, y_train)
best_params = lr_cv.best_params_

print(f"Best parameters: {best_params}")

2. K-nearest neighbors¶

from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
  • We create 2 different list, train and test score list which are empty at first
  • Fit the k-nearest neighbors classifier from the training dataset
  • For each K the accuracy score of train and test is append to the list score
In [45]:
train_score = []
test_score = []
neighbors = range(1, 31)

for k in neighbors:
    model = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    model.fit(x_train, y_train)
    train_score.append(accuracy_score(y_train, model.predict(x_train)))
    test_score.append(accuracy_score(y_test, model.predict(x_test)))

from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier

In [55]:
# We search for the accuracy score according to our database and the parameters we define
# citerion is a function to measure the quality of a split. 
#gini impurity measures the frequency at which any element of the dataset will be mislabelled when it is randomly labeled
#Entropy is a measure of information that indicates the disorder of the features with the target
#gini and entropy are quite similair
#splitter is the strategy used to choose the split at each node.

params = {"criterion":("gini", "entropy"), 
          "splitter":("best", "random"), 
          "max_depth":(list(range(1, 20))),

          }

tree_clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state= 50)

#n_jobs is the the number of jobs to run in parallel.

5. Random Forest Classifier Hyperparameter Tuning¶

  • Random forest algorithm builds a forest in the form of an ensemble of decision trees which adds more randomness while growing the trees.
  • While splitting a node, the algorithm searches for the best features from the random subset of features
  • Doc: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestClassifier.html?highlight=randomforestclassifier#sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestClassifier
In [58]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV

#max_features is the number of features to consider when looking for the best split
#n estimators is the number of the trees we want to build
n_estimators = [500, 900, 1100, 1500]
max_features = ['auto', None]
max_depth = [2, 3, 5, None]
min_samples_split = [2, 5, 10]
min_samples_leaf = [1, 2, 4]

params_grid = {
    'n_estimators': n_estimators, 
    'max_features': max_features,
    'max_depth': max_depth, 
    'min_samples_split': min_samples_split,
    'min_samples_leaf': min_samples_leaf
              }

rf_clf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=32)
rf_cv = GridSearchCV(rf_clf, params_grid, scoring="accuracy", cv=3, verbose=1, n_jobs=-1)
rf_cv.fit(x_train, y_train)
best_params = rf_cv.best_params_
print(f"Best parameters: {best_params}")

Fitting 3 folds for each of 288 candidates, totalling 864 fits

6. XGBoost Classifier Hyperparameter Tuning¶

  • The eXtreme Gradiant Boosting classifier is implemented instead of using sklern's version. Doc: https://xgboost.readthedocs.io/en/stable/
  • Given that the hyperparameters can be lists of numbers, it is better to perform a randomized search for imperparameters. With this, not all parameters will be tried but a random selection of parameters given a probability function to search in each parameter. Computation time is then more efficient. https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.model_selection.RandomizedSearchCV.html#sklearn.model_selection.RandomizedSearchCV
In [61]:
from xgboost import XGBClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV

param_grid = dict(
    n_estimators=stats.randint(10, 1000),
    max_depth=stats.randint(1, 10),
    learning_rate=stats.uniform(0, 1)
)

xgb_clf = XGBClassifier()


xgb_cv = RandomizedSearchCV(
    xgb_clf, param_grid, cv=3, n_iter=50, 
    scoring='accuracy', n_jobs=-1, verbose=1
)
xgb_cv.fit(x_train, y_train)
best_params = xgb_cv.best_params_
print(f"Best paramters: {best_params}")

Data Processing 2: Feature Selection¶

  • Feature selection will be performed on the training data set. Given the size of the training set, feature selection based on the correlation with the target will be performed.
  • The selection will be done by using the SelectPercentile Class on the sklearn library. The scoring function will be "mutual_info_classif" to account for any kind of relationship and not only linear correlation with the target.

  • The problem with the selection is that the number of features to keep is to be defined. For this task we decided to keep 40% of the original features and focus on the hyperparameters of the classifiers. Methods for cross validation can be performed to identify the optimal number of features to keep, this can be applied in future exercises.

  • Docummentation on Feature Selection: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/feature_selection.html

  • Documentation on Select Percentil class: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.feature_selection.SelectPercentile.html#sklearn.feature_selection.SelectPercentile
  • Documentation on the mutual information scoring function: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.feature_selection.mutual_info_regression.html#sklearn.feature_selection.mutual_info_regression
In [32]:
from sklearn.feature_selection import SelectPercentile
from sklearn.feature_selection import mutual_info_classif

x = df.drop(["Activity","activity_num"], axis = 1)
y = df["activity_num"]

selector = SelectPercentile(score_func = mutual_info_classif, percentile = 40).fit(X = x, y = y)
#an instance on the select percentile class is defined and trained on the training set.
In [36]:
x_train = selector.transform(X = x) #with the trained selector, the transformer keeps the variables with the highest correlation with the target. 
y_train = df["activity_num"]

x_test = selector.transform(X =df_test.drop(["Activity","activity_num"], axis = 1))
y_test = df_test["activity_num"]

2. K-nearest neighbors¶

In [40]:
from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
  • We create 2 different list, train and test score list which are empty at first
  • Fit the k-nearest neighbors classifier from the training dataset
  • For each K the accuracy score of train and test is append to the list score
In [41]:
train_score = []
test_score = []
neighbors = range(1, 31)

for k in neighbors:
    model = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=k)
    model.fit(x_train, y_train)
    train_score.append(accuracy_score(y_train, model.predict(x_train)))
    test_score.append(accuracy_score(y_test, model.predict(x_test)))
  • We will be plotting the relationship between the values of K and the corresponding testing accuracy. It will be done using matplotlib library.

In [47]:
from sklearn.svm import SVC
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV

svm_clf = SVC(kernel='rbf', gamma=0.1, C=1.0) #Create instance of the SVC class

params = {"C":(0.1, 0.5, 1, 2, 5, 10, 20), 
          "gamma":(0.001, 0.01, 0.1, 0.25, 0.5, 0.75, 1), 
          "kernel":('linear', 'poly', 'rbf')} #dict of parameters to try

4. Decision Tree Classifier¶

  • Now we approach the classification by a decision tree.
  • Doc: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.tree.DecisionTreeClassifier.html
In [51]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import GridSearchCV
In [52]:
# We search for the accuracy score according to our database and the parameters we define
# citerion is a function to measure the quality of a split. 
#gini impurity measures the frequency at which any element of the dataset will be mislabelled when it is randomly labeled
#Entropy is a measure of information that indicates the disorder of the features with the target
#gini and entropy are quite similair
#splitter is the strategy used to choose the split at each node.

params = {"criterion":("gini", "entropy"), 
          "splitter":("best", "random"), 
          "max_depth":(list(range(1, 20))), 
          "min_samples_split":[2, 3, 4], 
          "min_samples_leaf":list(range(1, 20))
          }

tree_clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state= 50)

#n_jobs is the the number of jobs to run in parallel.
tree_cv = GridSearchCV(tree_clf, params, scoring="accuracy", n_jobs=-1, verbose=1, cv=3)
tree_cv.fit(x_train, y_train)
best_params = tree_cv.best_params_
print(f'Best_params: {best_params}')

Fitting 3 folds for each of 4332 candidates, totalling 12996 fits
Best_params: {'criterion': 'gini', 'max_depth': 6, 'min_samples_leaf': 5, 'min_samples_split': 2, 'splitter': 'random'}
In [53]:
tree_clf = DecisionTreeClassifier(**best_params)

print_score(tree_clf, x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test, train=True)
print_score(tree_clf, x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test, train=False)

5. Random Forest Classifier¶

  • Random forest algorithm builds a forest in the form of an ensemble of decision trees which adds more randomness while growing the trees.
  • While splitting a node, the algorithm searches for the best features from the random subset of features
  • Doc: https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestClassifier.html?highlight=randomforestclassifier#sklearn.ensemble.RandomForestClassifier
In [57]:
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV

#max_features is the number of features to consider when looking for the best split
#n estimators is the number of the trees we want to build
n_estimators = [500, 900, 1100, 1500]
max_features = ['auto', None]
max_depth = [2, 3, 5, 10, 15, None]
min_samples_split = [2, 5, 10]
min_samples_leaf = [1, 2, 4]

params_grid = {
    'n_estimators': n_estimators, 
    'max_features': max_features,
    'max_depth': max_depth, 
    'min_samples_split': min_samples_split,
    'min_samples_leaf': min_samples_leaf
              }

rf_clf = RandomForestClassifier(random_state=32)
rf_cv = GridSearchCV(rf_clf, params_grid, scoring="accuracy", cv=3, verbose=1, n_jobs=-1)
rf_cv.fit(x_train, y_train)
best_params = rf_cv.best_params_
print(f"Best parameters: {best_params}")

Fitting 3 folds for each of 432 candidates, totalling 1296 fits
Best parameters: {'max_depth': None, 'max_features': 'auto', 'min_samples_leaf': 4, 'min_samples_split': 2, 'n_estimators': 500}

print_score(rf_clf, x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test, train=False)

6. XGBoost Classifier Hyperparameter Tuning¶

  • The eXtreme Gradiant Boosting classifier is implemented instead of using sklern's version. Doc: https://xgboost.readthedocs.io/en/stable/
  • Given that the hyperparameters can be lists of numbers, it is better to perform a randomized search for imperparameters. With this, not all parameters will be tried but a random selection of parameters given a probability function to search in each parameter. Computation time is then more efficient. https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.model_selection.RandomizedSearchCV.html#sklearn.model_selection.RandomizedSearchCV
In [60]:
from xgboost import XGBClassifier
from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV

param_grid = dict(
    n_estimators=stats.randint(10, 1000),
    max_depth=stats.randint(1, 10),
    learning_rate=stats.uniform(0, 1)
)

xgb_clf = XGBClassifier()


xgb_cv = RandomizedSearchCV(
    xgb_clf, param_grid, cv=3, n_iter=50, 
    scoring='accuracy', n_jobs=-1, verbose=1
)
xgb_cv.fit(x_train, y_train)
best_params = xgb_cv.best_params_
print(f"Best paramters: {best_params}")

Fitting 3 folds for each of 50 candidates, totalling 150 fits
Best paramters: {'learning_rate': 0.653614986830765, 'max_depth': 1, 'n_estimators': 187}
In [61]:

print_score(xgb_clf, x_train, y_train, x_test, y_test, train=False)
